Servo Motor Control
Starts at 28 minute mark of YouTube Video
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kUHmYKWwuWs&list=PLWNDWPAClRVpz1kldq3PktejQH3D-xRaC
OE disables when high, VCC comes from microcontroller
V+ is motor voltage (USE TERMINAL BLOCK INSTEAD... reverse polarity protected)
See Article at: https://dronebotworkshop.com/servo-motors-with-arduino/
Code is posted at Article address
Note that default I2C address is 0x40 for the PCA9685 (can change with address pads)
10K pots, 5-6 V power supply
SCL and SDA may not be on Arduino... use A5 and A4 instead
AdaFruit PWM library is used
#include //for I2C
May need to tweek MIN_PULSE_WIDTH and MAX_PULSE_WIDTH to get servo travel correct
FREQUENCY of 50 is standard for Servos
See Article: https://dronebotworkshop.com/i2c-arduino-arduino/
See Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PnG4fO5_vU4
SDA is bidirectional
Has pull-up resistors of about 10K
MIGHT have multiple Masters, HOWEVER, only one Master at a time can control
master generates the clock and has no address
Sketch at: https://dronebotworkshop.com/i2c-arduino-arduino/
In Slave, Wire.begin( SLAVE_ADDR ) // initialized device ase a Slave
Send blink rate from Master to Slave

Article: https://dronebotworkshop.com/i2c-part-2-build-i2c-sensor/
Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yBgikWNoU9o
7 address bits gives 128 slave devices (some are reserved)
SDA, entire byte is high or low for Start/Stop Signals

SCL drops low to signal begin of Data Transmission
Also signals whether in send or recieve mode.

bit 0 of data byte indicates direction
Opposite of Start Condition
4 UltraSonic Sensors
Uses NewPing library for UltraSonic Sensors
Video at: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=me7mhrRbspk
Article at: https://dronebotworkshop.com/i2c-arduino-raspberry-pi/
Needs bidirectional Voltage Level Convertor
I2C0 is for reading EEProm on Pi Hat Expansion Card (Nothing Else)
I2C1 is for anything else (3.3V)... Must be enabled
may or may not need to reboot after I2C config
should show i2c-1 in dev
If Pi is Master, then I2C will be 3.3 V (i.e. master dictates voltage of I2C)
MAKE SURE NOT 5V PULL-UPS IN CIRCUIT !!!
3.3V SDA and SCL to A4 and A5 of Arduino (3.3 will still register as HIGH)
Send ON/OFF signal to Arduino to switch LED
At 3.3V, will NOT achieve 1 meter distance for I2C
Will get 1 meter for I2C
Should be about 50 cents for each (dual channel)
Be sure it is BI-Directional for 3.3 V / 5 V (i.e. there are some that are UNI-Directional)
